snippet.textDisplay: @oskar recon Vaccines trigger the body's immune system to produce antibodies to a specific disease. The triggering mechanism can be anything from a similar virus (the use of relatively harmless cowpox virus to immunize against smallpox back in the 1790s), to a weakened form of the actual disease virus (early polio vaccines) to fragments of the virus that will trigger an immune response without causing the disease. Polio was eradicated by a massive inoculation campaign once the vaccine was developed. Clinical trials were started in 1954 just as a new polio epidemic was starting. In 1955 there were nearly 60,000 new polio cases just as the massive worldwide polio vaccination started. By 1957, there were only 6,000 new cases of polio in the US. Polio was eradicated in the developed world by the 1970s and exists today in only a few parts of Africa and Asia.

snippet.textDisplay: I definitely would like to learn more about this one! I know he's only going by what was said in the media by Oxford, but when it comes to DNA, I can't help but think of the CCR5 cell. I know that they reported that it doesn't effect our genetics, but it's way too soon to know that! When you think about HIV and the 2 receptors that it needs to have a binding affect, it's from CD4 and CCR5, but in people where the CCR5 was defective, you won't catch the virus. It wasn't until a few years ago that we learned how when you change your own CCR5 or completely get rid of it, that you lose an average of a third of your lifespan. So I am a skeptic, but if there was more transparency, I would be able to research it on my own, and not make a rash decision.

snippet.textDisplay:
Based on the information given in this video, I'm inclined to opt for the AstraZenica-Oxford
vaccine. One very important point you made, was that the other two vaccines may only
prevent symptoms of the disease, and not prevent infection, whereas the Oxford vaccine may
prevent both. And now, I want to raise another subject relative to vaccines, and SARS-CoV-2:
In a peer-reviewed article published in the American Journal of Microbiology, the authors presented strong associative evidence that vaccination with the MMR 11 (Measles, Mumps, Rubella) vaccine, can offer up to 70% protection against infection with the SARS-CoV-2 virus.
This happens because the viral signatures of those three viruses are quite similar to the the viral signature of the SARS-CoV-2 virus. The immune system of a person who has received the MMR 11 vaccine, recognizes the SARS-CoV-2 virus, because of that similarity to the other viruses, and attacks the SARS virus. Has your organization become aware of this research, and if so, will you address it, in a video?
